{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_alastor_ver02/data/sn78003992/0034058093A/1958061301/0324.xml":{"full_text":"Summit County Labor Nfews\n_ PmhHahmd Emmy Friday by\nTHE SUMMIT COUNTY LABOR NEWS\n4 Hmmpmpm pmbUthod bt Am lot faitrwtt of\nOrgmmimmi Labor mmd the entiro Community,\nEditorial, Advertising and Printing Offices\n920 SOUTH HIGH STREET Telephone\u2014PO 2-1110\nV AKRON 11, OHIO\nThe EXCHANGE PRINTING Co. ............Publisher\nMartin Bliman ...Editor\nAlex Eigenmacht.Contributing Editor\nEntered u Second due Matter May 4, 1923, at Poet Office at\nAkron, Ohio, under act of March 3, 1397.\nYearly Subscription in Advance...... .$8.00\nNews of Interest from the various local unions under the jurisdiction of\nthe Congress of Industrial Organizations, Akron Industrial Union\nS the American Federation of Labor and the Akron Federation of Labor is\nT sdldted. All news matter should reach the editorial office of the Summit\nCounty Labor News not later than Tuesday noon.\nThe Summit County Labor News accepts advertisements from firms not\non the unfair list of the Central Bodies. It must be understood, however,\nthat the editorial policy of this publication is affected in no way by such\nadvertisements.\nDepartment of Editorial Comment\n\u201cOur governor wants the Ohio Legislature to ban big adver\ntising signs on the interstate highway system. Meanwhile, his\naides disclose plans to use 400 outdoor posters in the fall political\ncampaign. The way things are going, Gov. Bill O\u2019Neill soon will\nbe known as Gov. Billboard O\u2019Neill.\u201d (Columnist Alvin Silver\nman, Cleveland Plain Dealer)\no\nLet\u2019s Make The Changes Permanent!\nIf a law is bad, you change it and make it better. You don\u2019t\nsay the change for the better will be effective for only a certain\nperiod and then the law goes back to being a bad lay again.\nWe have that kind of a situation facing the State Legislature\nin the special session that Governor C. William O\u2019Neill has an\nnounced for sometime during the month of June. The Governor\nsays he will recommend that the state\u2019s unemployment compen\nsation law be changed so compensation can be paid for 39 weeks\ninstead of the present 26 weeks.\nThe change is recommended because the heavy unemployment\nof the present recession has again emphasized the shortcomings of\nthe present law. When there is serious unemployment, the present\nlaw simply cannot do the job.\nBut there\u2019s a catch in the Governor\u2019s recommendation. It\u2019s\nonly a temporary change. Next year the law goes back again to\nthe 26-week limit. The Governor also has failed to indicate that\nhe favors an increase in the benefit rate.\nSo, what the Governor is recommending is this: Let\u2019s change\nthe law so that the unemployed in 1958 can receive our present in\nadequate compensation for 39 weeks but next year the jobless will\nbe able to receive the inadequate compensation for only 26 weeks!\nIt doesn\u2019t make sense.\nThe Executive Board of the Ohio AFL-CIO, at its first meet\ning since the merger convention, recommended this week that the\nLegislature improve the unemployment compensation law on a\npermanent basis rather than on a \u201ctemporary, stop-gap basis.\u201d\nThe Board recommended that the law be changed permanently\nso that the maximum weekly benefit equals 75 per cent of the inr\ndustrial worker's average weekly wage and that compensation be\npaid for 39 weeks.\nThe Board also reaffirmed Labor\u2019s contentioirthat the pres\nent unemployment compensation law permits the payment of\nsupplemental unemployment benefits (SUB) in addition to state\ncompensation.\nThe issue squarely before the Legislature is this: Ohio\u2019s un\nemployment compensation law is outdated. It needs moderniza\ntion. Let\u2019s get on with the job!\no\nAmerica The Loser\nTwo major anti-recession weapons have fallen by the political\nwayside, the victims of a doubtful coalition between a Republican\nAdministration and a Congress controlled by the GOP and con\nservative Democrats.\nIn the face of a 10-month-old recession, the nation\u2019s worst\nsince the end of World War II, the White House and the Demo\ncratic leadership in Congress have teamed up to block action on a\ntax cut for low and moderate-income families.\nWith 6.2 million unemployed\u2014and likely to reach 6 million in\nJune\u2014the Administration and the congressional coalitiion of Re\npublicans and conservative Democrats have defeated attempts to\npass a meaningful emergency unemployment compensation bill.\nThese actions, coming during a plummeting economy and in\nthe midst of world unrest that is testing America\u2019s leadership role,\ndisclose a queer mixture of political cynicism, timidity and fear.\nThe White House is committed to a \u201cmuddle through\u201d ap\nproach regardless of the cost to the nation in terms of present\nsuffering and lost economic growth. It is haunted by an unreal\nistic fear of budget deficits and a future inflation. It is con\nvinced that a do nothing timid approach to the recession eventu\nally will result in an economic cure.\nThe President has strongly resisted all attempts to bolster\nconsumer spending via a tax cut., His Administration has fought\noff attempts to write real legislation to aid the unemployed and\nsubstituted a measure that is best described as a cruel sham and\na hoax on the jobless.\nIt is disturbed about budget deficits when it is painfully ap\nparent that neither an economic recession nor Communist totali\ntarianism can be fought with balanced budgets.\nThe position of the Democrats is more difficult to understand.\nOriginally the proponents of an all-out anti-recession program,\n-their ardor has cooled.\nThere is some genuine concern that a tax cut would reduce\nrevenue at a time when America confronts many dangers in the\nworld.\nThere is also a political concern .that the Democratic party\n'may be saddled with blame for budget deficits and a future infla\ntionary spiral. Only a few bold members of the party see the eitua\n\u2022_ tion clearly.\nA handful of liberal Democrats have led the fight for mean\ningful jobless benefits but were outvoted in the main by Repub\ny Hqm* and conservative Democrats concerned with \u201cstate\u2019s rights.\u201d\nH* failure on the jobless aid bill, the decision against a tax\nmyna that Amsrica may wallow in the depths of the present\nrecession for many months to come\u20144f it doesn\u2019t get any worse.\nIt means also that the strong, dynamic America to whom the\nworld looks for leadership during present crises in France and the\ni, Middle East, nfky be a weakened, economically-ill nation iincapa\nhie of throwing it full strength into the fight for freedom.\nThe AFL-dO has pledged its Mt,\nstrength to drive to stamp out ex\nploitation of Puerto Rican workers in.\nNew York by assisting them to affilia\ntion with strong, dean unions.\nPresident George Mean? of the\nAFL-CIO said that a full-time or\nganiser from federation headquarters\nwould be assigned to the exclusive\nduty of working with the local tin.\nCIO Advisory Committee on Puerto\nRican Affhirs.\nHe made the announcement at a\nmeeting convened by the Central\nTrades and Labor Council, the Tn^ny.\ntrial Union Council, the Council of\nPuerto Rican Workers and spokes\nmen of the AFL-CIO Advisory Com\nmittee.\nThis committee, said Meany, must\nbe a permanent group which should\nintensify its activities \u201cin order to\ndo a better Job*\u2019, He pledged the\ncommittee national AFL-CIO coopera\ntion.\nIntroduced by Harry Van Arsdale,\nJr., president of the Central Trades\nand labor Council, Meany received a\nlong standing ovation from the sev\neral hundred Puerto Rican workers\nwho assembled In the Hotel Commo\ndore after their working boars. M\u00abmy\nrelated the struggles and exploita\ntion of Puerto Rican workers to\nperiods of similar social and economic\nexploitation in America of other\nimmigrant workers from Ireland,\nItaly bad Ocarist Russia.\n\"Hie trade union movement,\u201d he\nsaid, \u2018'has learned that discrimina\ntion is a barrier to trade union prog\nress. The purpose of trade unionism\nis simple\u2014to raise the standards of\nthose who work for wages. Low\nstandards are a threat to high stand\nards. We cannot maintain high stand\nards for a select few If we ignore\nthe conditions of those with low stand\nards.\u201d\nTurning to the problem of demo\ncratic control of unions, Meany em\nphasized that if a labor organization\nIs under domination of government, a\npolitical party, the \"Communist Party\nor racketeers, \u201cIt cannot be free to\nexpress the will of Its memberships.\nShameful abuse of Puerto Rican\nworkers in New York through \u201csweet\nheart\u201d contracts and \u201cquickie\u201d agree\nments between low-wage employers\nand labor racketeers baa long been a\nsource of concern to onions affiliated\nwith the AFL-CIO.\nThe McClellan special Senate com\nmittee last year provided documenta\ntion on the methods of \u201corganization\"\nand the connivance involved in deals\nbetween employers, their lawyers and\nunderworld elements preying on work\ners.\nJoseph Monserrat, head of the\nPuerto Rican labor office in New\nYork challenged meany\u2019s statement\nthat it would \u201ctake time\u201d to eliminate\nthe exploitation problem.\n\u201cThe reason we will go ahead,\u201d said\nMonserrat, \u201cmuch faster than did tits\nCITE RESPONSIBILITY FOR\nINDUSTRIAL AUTOMATION\nManagement has a positive respon\nsibility to devote some of the savings\ngained from introduction at new\nequipment to the easing\u2019 of adverse\neffects on workers.\nIf management takes this approach\nto the problem of automation and new\nmachines It can aid the economy gen\nerally without injury to labor, says\nthe current issue of Collective Bar\ngaining Report issued by the AFh\nCIO Dept, of Research.\nThe report notes that \"unions in the\nU. S. are not opposed and do not stand\nin the way of technological improve\nment.\u201d But unions are greatly con\ncerned about the manner in which\ntechnological chance is introduced.\nIn collective bargaining unions have\nsought the following protections:\n1\u2014Advance notice and consultation.\nUnions want to examine beforehand\nthe changes to be mads so that they\ncan minimise or eliminate adverse\neffects on workers.\nX\u2014Negotiation on questions raised\nby new conditions. The goal is to have\nthe worker benefit from new condi\ntions by negotiation on the content\nand classification of new and changed\njobs, wage ratee for theee Jobe, selec\ntion of workers to fin the Jobs and\nprovision for retraining to new duties.\nS\u2014Protection for affected workers.\nThe unions want sssnrsnrea far dis\nplaced workers that they be given\nfirst crack at other work, protection\nagainst wage loos by transfer and sev\nerance pay protection for those who\nmust be laid off.\nAffecting the problems of automa\ntion are collective bargaining goals\nwhich are not directly connected but\ncan do much to stsbtUse plants where\niqew equipment is introduced, onya the\nReport.\nAmong these are drives for short\ner hours, supplementary umsnploy\nimmigrants, j* taM the migrants\nfrom foreign countries \"didn\u2019t have\nttie George Meanys, the Van An\ndales, the Moe hafcmritiei, the Char* j\nlie Ztmmennaaa on their ride and an\nAFti-CIO to fight for them.\u201d Iushe\nwltz is secretary-treasurer of New\nYork City\u2019# Indnatrial Union Council.\nZimmerman la a vice president of the\nGarment Workers and Chairman of\nthe AFL-CIO OM Bights Committee.\nPrior to the mens meeting', Moony\nmot for three hours behind closed\ndoors with the AEl>dO Advisory\nCommittee to hammer out a program\nensuring local and national coopera\ntion to meet the racketeering prob\nlem in New York.\nMental Health\nIs Discussed\nIn Booklet\nMaintenance of an acceptable\nstandard of living, adequate housing,\na good school system and the ab\nsence of prejudice and discrimination\nare keys to good mental health, the\nAFL-CIO says hi a new booklet, The\nWorker\u2019s Stake in Mental Health.\nPublished by the labor movement\u2019s\nCommunity Service Activities in co\noperation with the National Associa\ntion for Mental Health, the booklet\nalso lists stable family life, reason\nably good physical health, the avail\nability of Job opportunities, the ex\nistence of machinery to settle on-the\nJob disputes and the opportunity for\nsufficient relaxation and recreation\nas being among other factors indls\npensible in preventing mental illness.\nThe pamphlet cites statistics show\ning that more thin 700,000 patients\n\"are crowded Into the country\u2019s too\nfew mental hospitals,\u201d adding that\nthe present rate of admissions indi\ncate that one out of every 10 per\nsons hi the United States \u201cwill spend\nsome part of Wa life in a mental in\nstitution.\u201d\n'f\nThe APL-CSIO Says that the price\ntag on mental illness runs to more\nthan $1 billion JpmuaUy, with be\ntween 60 and 80 her cent of all lost\nwork thus resuMfcg from emotional\ndisturbances.\nCovering mental illness, medical\nguidance and treatment In general,\nnon-technlcal terms, the publication\nplace* considerable emphasis on re\nhabilitation, union action for mental\nhealth, some recommended local un\nion projects and a mental health check\nlist to aid onions in assessing the\nquality and scope of mental health\nprograms and treatment facilities in\ntheir local community.\nCopies of the booklet can be ob\ntained through AFL-CIO Community\nService Activities, 9 Fast 40th St.,\nNew York 18, New York.\nmeat benefits and improved pension\nplans allowing for earlier retirement,\nvesting, etc.\nHie Report illustrates the approach\nto automation and technological\nchange with three case histories cov\nering elevator operators, railway\nclerks and refinery workers.\nNew City Building i\nIs Presented by\nLabor Group\nThe Budding Construction Trades\nCouncil in Wichita, Kan., has turned\nover to the town of UdaU, Kan. a new\nfire station and city office building\nwith the compliments of organized\nlabor.\nHie formal dedication and turning\nover of the actual building climaxed\na 30-month effort by organized labor\nto replace the fire station and cftioe\nbuilding destroyed by a tornado in\nHay 1956. i _\nThe stiuetura was built by.MO\nunion men who donated their week\nends and spare time aided s\u2014isiy\nby 19 unions In the area and over. 49\ncontractors.'\nTbs project was oigaateed by H. B.\nMooney,' business .representative of\nthe Wichita Ciounoffto help the strick\nen town. Tbs new building houses the\ntown's two fire trucks, the city cleric's\noffice, a library and workroom for\ncity maintenance employes.\nAFL-dO Pres. Oaorga Meany, In\na letter to Mooney, expressed his\ngratification at (m role of labor in\nsetting up the projiot He added:\ndales upon the lias spirit ef coopera\nte tU* vakiataer ank* \u25a0'MMj\n\u2018All Nation Festival\u2019 Features\nStan Hywet Hall Anniversary\nOoiorful font .dances mudc\ntom all part* of the world win be on\ntiie program when Stan Hywct Hall\nobserves its first anniversary as\ncultural center Sunday.\nNationality groups in native drew\nWin participate In the afternoon pro*\nfrom. It lo being billed as nn \u201cAH\nNations Festival\u2019'\nIn addition to the musical program,\nto be carried out amid a display of\nad the world\u2019s flags, girls in native\ncostumes will seU many of tile na\ntional deJicaciee of the countries rep\nresented. fv\nThis la only part of the unusual\nprogram being planned, according to\nMrs. Boro Pavlovich of Akron, chair\nman of the event.\nThe nationality groups scheduled to;\ntake part include:\n1) Akron\u2019s Isidor Bajlch Serbian\nFolk dancers, accompanied by the\nEmery Otecnl string orchestra\nRussian choral groups from Ak\nron's St. Nicholas Church.\n3) Rumanian folk dancers from the'\nAkron Rumanian Orthodox Church.\n4) A Greek a capella choir from\ntile Akron Greek Orthodox Church.\n5) Greek folk dancers from the\nAkron Greek Orthodox .Church.\n6) Israeli folk dancers from the\nAkron Jewish Center.\n7) A Hungarian gypsy orchestra\ncomposed of Akron Hungarian refu\ngees.\n8) Macedonian Bulgarian folk\ndancers from the St Elia Orthodox\nChurch.\n9) Magyar American teen age\nfolk dancers.\n10) Barberton\u2019s American-Slovene\nSociety singers and dancers.\n\nXI) Patch diahn from Akna*s\nDatch Chib.\nU) Irlslr dMCen from Am An\ncient Order of Hibernians.\nNationality groups throughout the\narea are being contacted to provide\nhotne-made delicacies Which will be\nsold on the grounds during the festi\nval Ingredients for the foodstuffs\nwill be paid for by the Stan Hywet\nFoundation and profits from the sales\nwill be used for restoration of the\ncultural center.\nAmong the delicacies, to be add are\nBacklava (Greek), Zelenica (Slovene),\nStrudel (Hungarian), Serbian crape\nsuzebte, Pita (Serbian) and numerous\nRumanian pastries,\nThe pregram will be divided Into\ntwo parts from 3:00 to 5:00 P. M.\nand from OHIO to 8:00 P. M. No addi\ntional fees will be charged for the\nfestival Regular admission to Stan\nHywet grounds is 50 cents for adults\nmid 25 cento for children.\n(Pol. Adv.)\nGeorge D. Cline\nfor\nState Senator\n(4 Year Term)\n7-8-58\nV\u2018V\nHow many of\nthese ways\ndo you put\nelectricity\nto work?\n(Atumrt b*tow)\nThe hands in these pictures are\nputting electricity to work in 9\nways. Look at them carefully.\nHow many of these jobs do you\ndo electrically? And how many\notheraf\nCount them and see. You'll prob\nably find you put your depend\nable electricity to work every day.\nin many, more ways than you\nrealize.\nCan you think of anything else\nthat gives you\nso little cost?\nV\nA*\nCall Confab;\nta MWn to Mcbeirttt,\nattendantMwffltacto\nDirector Alexander\nant Director William J. McSorley, Jr,\nDirector of Hceeareh Henry Sea,\nSpecial Bepreaeateitae Fkl% Wdjlt;\n\u25a0dan. Women\u2019* Go-Director*\nMurray and Margaret\nand Area Director* Hngh MnHIn\nDarrell Smith.\nHie meeting will be one of a\nof 8 to he held in key dtiaa through\nout the nation tM* year.\nBusdmss Register\nPeacock Nursery\nTry\" U* Pot Better Plant*1\nOURS 'GROW\ntv- -i.\n\nfc :-T\n-V;\na-\u2018^ 5*-\nMO 6-4922 J\n721 S. CI*r*l*ad-M*\u00ab*illoa Reed\n\u25a0{p'\n6-27\nAKRON, OHIO\nCanpfltM Hiekaiaa\nFuneral Homo .\u2022**.r* v\nFUNERAL DIRECTOR\nO** 24 Hour Ambulance Service\nOxygen Equipped\n566 Park Ay*., W. SH 5-1161\nBAM EXTON. OHIO\n9-5\nFred Arbogast fr Co., Inc.\nMaker* of''\nJITTER BUG HAWAIIAN WIGGLER\nHULA POPPER\n313 West Norik Street BL 3-2177\nAKRON 4, OHIO\n9-5\nEast Akron Insurance Agency\nGENERAL INSURANCE\nE. A. Wagner, Manager\n915 E. Market Street PO 2*7615\nAKRON, OHIO\n9-5\nDemand ThU Label on -,n\nYour Printing .v\nAkron Allied Printing\nTrades CoancH\nBOX 127 AKRON 9, OHIO\n7-11\n1 Original Barbacua Mafic\nRIB STEAK AND CHICKEN DINNERS\n52 Irt Madia* Straat BL1.0157\nAKRON, OHIO\n8-29 -r'.\nNorman C. WhMay; M.T. J\nArthritis Lumbago Nervousnass\nConstipation Paralysis Insomnia, Etc.\nMASSAGE and CABINET BATHS\nMake An Appointment Today.\n1930 I Irii Straat SW 4-7972\nCUYAHOGA FALLS, OHIO\n6-13 _\nBud's Outboard Motor Mart\nB\u00b0\u00b0ts and Motors\u2014Now and i run 1011\nService\u2014Parts\u2014Moster-Craft and Tee-Nee\nTrailers\u2014Fiber Glass products\u2014-Chris-Craft\nf*t>ef0k\u201c Boole\u2014Tomahawk\nv u puracroft Aluminum Boots\nX? ?w ,Jac** Molded Plywood foctory Au\nthor zed <^rv Irm ITT\naListe.\n.....wviTiva tor UMmp\n\u2014Elgin\u2014Sea Flyer\u2014Saa\nVoyager.\nTrades Terms Motors' to Rant\n2045 Gia\n6-27\n\u2022aoatAve. PR 3-3*07\nAKRON, OHIO\nLton't Tavorn\nFine Food for Bonquets and Parties\nACCOMMODATIONS FOR 160 PERSONS\n1349 E. Tsllmadga Am. Ml 3-2511\nAKRON, OHIO\n7-25\nWattan Lawnmawar Supply\nNEW HAND AND POWER MOWERS\nSharpening Repairing Porta\nSeeds Fertilizers Toole\n143t Cealev Read UN 4-0115\n7-25\nAKRON OHIO\n;V.\nSandy Baach FaHt\nWHER